Below is a thread about a possible AO Design mistake.  Here's the link:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://aoforums.funcom.com/showthread.php?s=9f98d404e9dd19ac7d937a51cfd1f887&threadid=24762">aoforums.funcom.com/showt...adid=24762</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Here is the first paragraph of the thread:<br>
<br>
After reading the posts on TCP and UDP, which are the two protocols that info is transmited across the web, it appears that Funcom opted to use TCP. Now EQ and AO both use UDP because, even tho its harder to code, it is made for streaming audio and video transfers. TCP, tho better in certain ways for more static info transfer, breaks down if ALL the info is not recieved from the source. This is why it cannot be used for live preformances. Online games are similer to live performances in that they exist in real time. <br>
<br>
Im not going to go further into the technical side of it as that has been already done by more versed folks than myself. I am simply going to make a supposition based on the knowledge I recieved by reading about this. <br>
<br>
Why would Funcom release a game they knew was unfinished? Because maybe its NOT unfinished. Its totally finished. It works great in the offices of Funcom and prob worked pretty well everywhere till Beta 3 hit. At that time, larger numbers of people began to log on and use it. It was then that the problem of the File Transfer Protocol (FTP) began to rear its ugly head. <br>
<br>
The problem became even worse in B4 when several times that number began to log on. Now its totally out of control with the influx of all the new paying customers. Add the possible existance of substandard servers (Exodus) and now you have a real nightmare. <br>
<br>
To fix this problem would mean that Funcom would have to start from scratch building new code designed to use UDP like EQ and AC do and its way to late for that. <br>
<br>
If Im right about this, then that explains many things. It explains why they went ahead and released it. There was no sense in holding on to it to try and &quot;fix&quot; it because to recode from scratch would take months, maybe years. <br>
<br>
So they went ahead, took a chance and released it because basically they have nothing to lose at this point. <br>
<br>
Now they are looking for a miracle to save them from a basic programming decision they made years ago. They made it because it made their job easier at the time and they took a chance it would be ok. At the time they made it, Im sure it seemed like a good choice. It was probably made before either EQ or AC had been released and it would have added more code in that they would have to tweak the UDP to do what they needed. FTP, on the other hand, uses the users operating system (OS) to do all the work so no code is needed for that. <br>
<br>
I could go into more detail, but if you are interested in the mechanics of what I am talking about, you can read for yourselves like I did under the posts concerning FTP and UDP. I suggest you do. <br>
<br>
All I can do now is hope Im wrong. While some disagree that this is the case, there are some that believe it is and after weighing both sides, this seems to be the most logical reason for all the problems that I can see. <br>
<br>
To everyone who has bought the game, good luck. You may need it.<br>
