<br>
If you buy a brand new DVD and find a scratch on it.<br>
<br>
With a TCP DVD player it would just stop playing. To fix it you would have to run to the store and return the DVD for a new one.<br>
<br>
With a UDP DVD player it would just skip over the scratch your TV would flicker for a couple seconds and then continue playing the rest of the film.<br>
<br>
TCP doesn't allow for any errors at all and will go to all extremes to ensure you have good data whether it takes a min or a day to fix the problem.<br>
<br>
UDP is a bare protocol which doesn't acknowlege if there are any errors in transmission. It's up to the programmer to decide how to handle loss packets and whether to request retransmits.<br>
<br>
They would have to almost completely reprogram the client to accept UDP and resolve packet loss situations. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/udreadstar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>dreadstar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Dervish Cutthroat</span><br>  Posts: 151<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/3/01 5:09:32 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: UDP vs TCP</span><hr size=1> from <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.webopedia.com/">www.webopedia.com/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> (zdnet)<br>
<br>
UDP:  Short for User Datagram Protocol, a connectionless protocol that, like TCP, runs on top of IP networks. Unlike TCP/IP, UDP/IP provides very few error recovery services, offering instead a direct way to send and receive datagrams over an IP network. It's used primarily for broadcasting messages over a network. <br>
<br>
TCP:  Abbreviation of Transmission Control Protocol, and pronounced as separate letters. TCP is one of the main protocols in TCP/IP networks. Whereas the IP protocol deals only with packets, TCP enables two hosts to establish a connection and exchange streams of data. TCP guarantees delivery of data and also guarantees that packets will be delivered in the same order in which they were sent. <br>
